00:14:19,275 --> 00:14:21,569
But it was, like, a huge...

256
00:14:21,652 --> 00:14:22,653
You can say it.

257
00:14:22,736 --> 00:14:24,613
It was, like, a huge bump in the road.

258
00:14:24,697 --> 00:14:28,158
You were going to live this normal life,
and then your husband became president.

259
00:14:28,450 --> 00:14:32,079
So how does it feel, trying to get back
on the track of your normal life

260
00:14:32,162 --> 00:14:33,247
that you had before?

261
00:14:33,330 --> 00:14:36,083
What I've learned is,
"Get back on what track?"

262
00:14:36,166 --> 00:14:37,751
It's a whole new track.

263
00:14:37,835 --> 00:14:39,712
It's not going back. It's not...

264
00:14:39,795 --> 00:14:43,340
You know, it's just all different,
and it's different forever.

265
00:14:43,549 --> 00:14:45,843
So it's not getting back on track,

266
00:14:45,926 --> 00:14:48,345
but it's creating my next track.

267
00:14:48,596 --> 00:14:50,097
I'm doing what you're doing.

268
00:14:50,180 --> 00:14:52,975
I'm figuring out, "What do I want to do?

269
00:14:53,058 --> 00:14:54,435
What do I care about?"

270
00:14:55,352 --> 00:14:58,522
And it takes time to process your life

271
00:14:58,606 --> 00:15:01,191
and figure out what it all means.

272
00:15:01,609 --> 00:15:05,487
So little of who I am
happened in those eight years.

273
00:15:05,571 --> 00:15:08,866
So much more of who I was
happened before.

274
00:15:13,454 --> 00:15:16,206
So are you guys going to take
a final look when you're done

275
00:15:16,290 --> 00:15:19,043
at the monitors in the foyer?

276
00:15:20,961 --> 00:15:22,463
Mrs. Obama's ready.

277
00:15:24,632 --> 00:15:26,050
I'm ready, too.

278
00:15:27,676 --> 00:15:29,970
So tell us about Michelle Obama
as a little girl,

279
00:15:30,220 --> 00:15:32,222
because she says she was feisty,

280
00:15:32,431 --> 00:15:34,558
and that part of you
really liked her feistiness.

281
00:15:34,642 --> 00:15:35,893
- True?
- I did.

282
00:15:35,976 --> 00:15:38,479
Well, it goes back to Craig.

283
00:15:38,896 --> 00:15:41,649
I think I was too soft with him,

284
00:15:41,732 --> 00:15:43,734
trying to make him the nice little boy,

285
00:15:43,817 --> 00:15:45,861
- That's right.
- And I don't think that works.

286
00:15:45,945 --> 00:15:47,321
So I just...

287
00:15:47,404 --> 00:15:48,906
She was too soft on you.

288
00:15:50,866 --> 00:15:53,243
No, she made me too soft.

289
00:15:53,661 --> 00:15:55,079
She was too strict.

290
00:15:55,454 --> 00:15:58,165
Your sister took the brunt of that.
I hope you feel bad.

291
00:15:59,375 --> 00:16:01,043
Do you feel
you have your life back?

292
00:16:01,126 --> 00:16:02,544
Do you miss the White House at all?

293
00:16:02,962 --> 00:16:03,921
- No.
- No?

294
00:16:04,004 --> 00:16:05,047
Not at all.

295
00:16:06,674 --> 00:16:08,509
- All right. Bye, team.
- OK. All right.

296
00:16:09,510 --> 00:16:11,971
- I'll see you guys tonight.
- OK. All right.

297
00:16:12,054 --> 00:16:13,347
- Bye.
- Bye.

298
00:16:14,890 --> 00:16:17,726
- Hello.
- I thought you were wearing the pink.

299
00:16:17,810 --> 00:16:20,604
No, that was for earlier,
and that had food on it.

300
00:16:20,688 --> 00:16:22,439
That's the evening attire.

301
00:16:22,523 --> 00:16:25,943
- That was for the day.
- That looks like two belts.

302
00:16:26,235 --> 00:16:29,238
It's one belt, but it's three separate...

303
00:16:29,738 --> 00:16:31,699
Oh, it's got a top belt, too.

304
00:16:31,782 --> 00:16:33,826
- Oh, I see.
- Yep, this, this, and this.

305
00:16:33,909 --> 00:16:35,119
But it's not separated?

306
00:16:35,202 --> 00:16:37,913
No. It's one belt,
but you buckle it three different times.

307
00:16:37,997 --> 00:16:40,582
And is that the style,
to have your belt so high now?

308
00:16:43,210 --> 00:16:44,211
Is that the style?

309
00:16:44,294 --> 00:16:46,171
- I don't know...
- People, what's so...

310
00:16:46,255 --> 00:16:49,174
- I don't...
- I just asked if it was the style.

311
00:16:49,258 --> 00:16:50,801
It isn't about you.

312
00:16:50,884 --> 00:16:52,261
Come on, zip it. Let's go.

313
00:16:52,344 --> 00:16:55,347
That was a compliment.
I like the belt up that high.

314
00:16:55,431 --> 00:16:57,850
- I don't know what people...
- It looks like a holster.

315
00:16:57,933 --> 00:16:59,351
Like, if you had some...

316
00:16:59,810 --> 00:17:02,730
- You could. It's when I...
- You shouldn't laugh.

317
00:17:02,813 --> 00:17:05,691
- That's what I was talking about.
- That's the problem.

318
00:17:05,774 --> 00:17:06,775
Come on, Craig.

319
00:17:08,569 --> 00:17:10,487
My brother, my big brother...

320
00:17:10,571 --> 00:17:13,657
You know, he was my first crush,
my big brother.

321
00:17:14,074 --> 00:17:16,702
My brother's the kind of person...
Everybody liked Craig.

322
00:17:17,411 --> 00:17:20,497
You know,
my mother liked Craig better than me.

323
00:17:21,081 --> 00:17:22,875
I joke about this all the time.

324
00:17:22,958 --> 00:17:26,045
You know, we would have Thanksgiving
at the White House.

325
00:17:26,128 --> 00:17:28,672
And I'd be around.
There would be butlers and stuff going on.

326
00:17:28,756 --> 00:17:30,257
And, "Where's Craig?

327
00:17:32,134 --> 00:17:33,510
But when's Craig coming?"

328
00:17:33,594 --> 00:17:36,263
And I was like, "Ma. Come on, lady.

329
00:17:36,346 --> 00:17:39,558
I am the First Lady.
What more do I have to do?"

330
00:17:41,185 --> 00:17:42,311
You know? I mean...

331
00:17:47,066 --> 00:17:49,151
Everybody in the world
knows who she is.

332
00:17:49,359 --> 00:17:50,861
That's incredible.

333
00:17:50,944 --> 00:17:53,489
Everybody in the world knows
who my sister is.

334
00:17:53,822 --> 00:17:55,324
What is that? That's dumb.

335
00:17:55,407 --> 00:17:57,618
Nobody should have
to deal with that. No one.

336
00:17:58,160 --> 00:18:00,454
No brother should have
to deal with their sister

337
00:18:00,537 --> 00:18:03,040
being the most popular person
in the world.

338
00:18:13,425 --> 00:18:15,928
- Ooh, it's chilly. Hey, Mommy.
- It is chilly.

339
00:18:16,178 --> 00:18:18,639
- Sorry for the snow.
- Take you on a tour...?

340
00:18:19,264 --> 00:18:21,558
If it weren't for you,
we'd put the blinds up.

341
00:18:22,142 --> 00:18:22,976
Yeah.

342
00:18:23,060 --> 00:18:25,437
- That's a preference.
- Is she allowed...

343
00:18:27,022 --> 00:18:29,566
Are those people terrorists?
Are they going to attack?

344
00:18:29,650 --> 00:18:31,860
- See, that's not right.
- No.

345
00:18:32,111 --> 00:18:34,696
Craig always has a good supply of wine.

346
00:18:34,780 --> 00:18:38,242
- Right. So we have some kale salad.
- I love coming here and drinking his wine.

347
00:18:38,325 --> 00:18:39,743
I have wine, too.

348
00:18:40,327 --> 00:18:43,330
- I know...
- Did you see it? China, you still saw it.

349
00:18:43,413 --> 00:18:45,040
I've got wine, too.

350
00:18:45,499 --> 00:18:46,542
That's right.

351
00:18:46,625 --> 00:18:48,460
I get the special wine.

352
00:18:48,710 --> 00:18:50,587
Mich just gets White House wine.

353
00:18:50,671 --> 00:18:52,965
"When I come to Craig's house..."

354
00:18:53,423 --> 00:18:55,050
That's right, Ma. You tell her.

355
00:18:56,009 --> 00:18:58,428
"...I just get... The wine is just..."

356
00:18:58,512 --> 00:19:01,515
- I'm going to have some of this wine.
- Here's some of my wine.

357
00:19:01,598 --> 00:19:02,933
Here, refill mine.

358
00:19:03,016 --> 00:19:05,227
Let me see. Wait, let me see. Let me see.

359
00:19:05,310 --> 00:19:06,311
Family.

360
00:19:07,104 --> 00:19:08,981
These are my favorite pictures.

361
00:19:13,610 --> 00:19:15,529
God, that tree looks ugly.

362
00:19:15,612 --> 00:19:18,198
Because you actually let us
decorate the tree.

363
00:19:18,282 --> 00:19:19,867
That's why it looks ugly.

364
00:19:20,534 --> 00:19:22,661
Because a seven-year-old did that.

365
00:19:22,828 --> 00:19:24,538
Oh, here's the...

366
00:19:24,621 --> 00:19:26,123
Oh, there's the dress.

367
00:19:26,331 --> 00:19:28,876
You can see all these pleats.

368
00:19:28,959 --> 00:19:30,669
Look how pretty you are, Mommy.

369
00:19:30,752 --> 00:19:33,213
- Could have been on TV, in movies.
- So young.

370
00:19:33,839 --> 00:19:36,758
- Were you excited about your wedding?
- I think so.

371
00:19:37,467 --> 00:19:40,262
At least you weren't pregnant,
because I didn't come until later.

372
00:19:40,345 --> 00:19:41,722
"I might have been happy about it."

373
00:19:42,014 --> 00:19:44,057
I haven't seen it in a long time, but...

374
00:19:45,809 --> 00:19:46,935
that was good.

375
00:19:48,103 --> 00:19:49,271
That was good.

376
00:19:50,147 --> 00:19:53,275
Do you know, the last time
we went through these pictures like this

377
00:19:53,358 --> 00:19:54,818
had to be when Dad was alive.

378
00:19:54,902 --> 00:19:55,903
Sure.

379
00:19:56,486 --> 00:19:58,447
He just liked people.

380
00:19:58,989 --> 00:20:00,824
Look how handsome Dad is.

381
00:20:09,374 --> 00:20:12,127
I am from the South Side of Chicago.

382
00:20:14,588 --> 00:20:18,258
That tells you as much about me
as you need to know.

383
00:20:19,468 --> 00:20:22,638
It was a typical working-class community.

384
00:20:22,971 --> 00:20:24,264
Some good music,

385
00:20:24,348 --> 00:20:25,933
some good barbecue,

386
00:20:26,016 --> 00:20:27,184
some good times.

387
00:20:32,856 --> 00:20:37,736
Our dinner table was the first table
where I felt like I belonged.

388
00:20:38,820 --> 00:20:40,948
And then you go out into the world

389
00:20:41,031 --> 00:20:43,659
expecting the same thing.

390
00:20:46,662 --> 00:20:48,247
You're in high school,

391
00:20:48,664 --> 00:20:50,207
you are accomplished.

392
00:20:50,540 --> 00:20:53,335
You were class treasurer?
Do I remember that right?

393
00:20:53,418 --> 00:20:55,587
I was senior class treasurer, yes.

394
00:20:55,671 --> 00:20:57,172
I was still that kid.

395
00:20:59,424 --> 00:21:01,551
You were on the honor roll,

396
00:21:02,469 --> 00:21:04,721
and you went to go see
your guidance counselor.

397
00:21:04,805 --> 00:21:06,598
Your brother had gone to Princeton,

398
00:21:06,682 --> 00:21:09,643
and you thought, "I'm going to aspire
to go to Princeton, too."

399
00:21:09,726 --> 00:21:11,645
But that guidance counselor
had other ideas,

400
00:21:12,020 --> 00:21:14,481
didn't see in you
what you saw in yourself.

401
00:21:14,564 --> 00:21:18,193
Yeah, and she decided
that my wish to go to Princeton

402
00:21:18,652 --> 00:21:20,153
was thinking too big,

403
00:21:20,237 --> 00:21:21,655
that I was reaching too high.

404
00:21:21,738 --> 00:21:24,908
And at that point, she told me,
"I don't think you're Princeton material."

405
00:21:25,284 --> 00:21:26,743
- The nerve!
- Yeah.

406
00:21:28,912 --> 00:21:30,872
- Well, she was wrong.
- Yeah.

407
00:21:33,125 --> 00:21:36,128
I went back to the school just recently
and the principal was like,

408
00:21:36,211 --> 00:21:38,130
"She doesn't work here anymore."

409
00:21:40,924 --> 00:21:42,634
I was like, "I bet she doesn't."

410
00:21:44,261 --> 00:21:47,222
I share that
because obviously it worked out OK.

411
00:21:49,433 --> 00:21:54,104
But that statement, while I was able
to get over it, it was a punch.

412
00:21:54,313 --> 00:21:56,231
I'm still a little salty...

413
00:21:57,733 --> 00:21:58,859
...about that.

414
00:22:01,194 --> 00:22:02,946
Still a little salty about it.

415
00:22:13,415 --> 00:22:14,791
Your book really stuck to me,

416
00:22:15,208 --> 00:22:18,503
how there's just so much
that African-American women go through

417
00:22:18,587 --> 00:22:21,381
and African-American individuals
go through, as a whole.

418
00:22:21,631 --> 00:22:24,301
And we go through those alone.

419
00:22:24,384 --> 00:22:26,762
We don't have backup.
We don't have support.

420
00:22:27,220 --> 00:22:29,473
With me being a first-generation student,

421
00:22:29,556 --> 00:22:31,558
I've lived in subsidized housing
all my life.

422
00:22:31,641 --> 00:22:33,435
I didn't believe that I would be sitting

423
00:22:33,518 --> 00:22:35,812
next to the former First Lady
of the United States.

424
00:22:36,229 --> 00:22:39,274
And I just wanted to know,
how did you, as a black woman,

425
00:22:39,358 --> 00:22:42,277
persevere through, just, invisibility?

426
00:22:42,694 --> 00:22:46,114
For me, I never felt invisible.

427
00:22:46,448 --> 00:22:51,787
And I think, in thinking through my story
about why do I not now feel invisible,

428
00:22:51,995 --> 00:22:54,414
I think it's because my parents

429
00:22:54,915 --> 00:22:58,043
made me always feel visible.

430
00:22:58,543 --> 00:23:01,755
It came from
not what was going on in the world,

431
00:23:02,047 --> 00:23:04,466
but what was going on at my dinner table.

432
00:23:04,758 --> 00:23:07,344
My mother, she let us ask anything.

433
00:23:07,552 --> 00:23:08,762
You had to be polite.

434
00:23:08,929 --> 00:23:11,723
We got spankings if we were too...
You know?

435
00:23:12,307 --> 00:23:14,059
She was still a black mother.

436
00:23:14,851 --> 00:23:19,189
But that invisibility, it starts here.

437
00:23:19,398 --> 00:23:24,945
We can't afford to wait for the world
to be equal to start feeling seen.

438
00:23:25,028 --> 00:23:25,946
We're far from it.

439
00:23:26,279 --> 00:23:27,781
Time will not allow it.

440
00:23:27,864 --> 00:23:30,450
It's not going to happen
with one president, one vote.

441
00:23:30,659 --> 00:23:33,995
So you've got to find the tools
within yourself to feel visible,

442
00:23:34,079 --> 00:23:36,456
and to be heard, and to use your voice.

443
00:23:40,627 --> 00:23:43,505
I have high expectations of young people.

444
00:23:44,214 --> 00:23:47,634
It's the same expectations
my family had of me.

445
00:23:50,220 --> 00:23:54,224
My grandfather Dandy
expected us to be great.

446
00:23:55,600 --> 00:23:58,812
But he went through life
being underestimated.

447
00:24:01,189 --> 00:24:04,443
Growing up, he was a brilliant young man,

448
00:24:04,734 --> 00:24:06,653
somebody that loved to read books,

449
00:24:06,736 --> 00:24:10,157
loved to delve into things
in a deep and meaningful way.

450
00:24:11,992 --> 00:24:14,995
He could have been a professor.
He could have been a doctor.

451
00:24:15,996 --> 00:24:18,582
But because of race and class,

452
00:24:18,874 --> 00:24:21,793
he couldn't get into colleges.

453
00:24:22,210 --> 00:24:24,337
He didn't have the money, the resources...

454
00:24:25,547 --> 00:24:28,008
And imagine walking around
with all this ability,

455
00:24:28,091 --> 00:24:30,051
and the world telling you, "No.

456
00:24:30,135 --> 00:24:32,137
No, you're not good enough.
No, you're not ready."

457
00:24:32,220 --> 00:24:35,557
Watching people half your intelligence

458
00:24:35,640 --> 00:24:37,517
being promoted past you.

459
00:24:37,601 --> 00:24:40,270
You know,
watching opportunities slip away,

460
00:24:40,353 --> 00:24:43,857
not because you're not able,
but because nobody thinks you deserve it.

461
00:24:46,109 --> 00:24:49,988
That caused him
a lot of disappointment and anger.

462
00:24:50,071 --> 00:24:52,949
That made him push us to be better.

463
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:03,710
This is a super-normal Wednesday.

464
00:25:04,711 --> 00:25:05,754
Very normal.

465
00:25:06,796 --> 00:25:10,425
Every so often a book comes along
that creates bridges.

466
00:25:10,509 --> 00:25:11,343
Yeah.

467
00:25:11,426 --> 00:25:14,429
So we thought it was a great idea
to bring two book clubs together

468
00:25:14,513 --> 00:25:17,307
to talk about
their unique experiences with the book,

469
00:25:17,390 --> 00:25:19,059
but also the common things.

470
00:25:19,142 --> 00:25:21,311
- You come from Chicago, also.
- My parents.

471
00:25:21,394 --> 00:25:23,355
- Where did you grow up?
- My mom's from Gresham.

472
00:25:23,438 --> 00:25:25,023
That's where Barack organized.

473
00:25:25,106 --> 00:25:29,152
But it was fascinating to read
because they were lifelong,

474
00:25:29,236 --> 00:25:32,030
they lived there, they grew up there,
family there, steeped there.

475
00:25:32,322 --> 00:25:34,783
And they were definitely
part of the white flight.

476
00:25:35,242 --> 00:25:37,369
Do you have a sense
of what they were fleeing

477
00:25:37,452 --> 00:25:38,495
when they decided to leave?

478
00:25:38,578 --> 00:25:39,871
Or did they even know?

479
00:25:39,955 --> 00:25:41,957
I don't know that my parents did.

480
00:25:42,040 --> 00:25:44,417
If you look at my parents' parents,

481
00:25:44,501 --> 00:25:47,128
that's when you see the veiled racism.

482
00:25:47,796 --> 00:25:50,590
That's when you would hear
the off-the-cuff remarks

483
00:25:50,674 --> 00:25:53,051
like, "Well, they're moving
into the neighborhood."

484
00:25:53,134 --> 00:25:57,931
And it was so interesting to read that
from your perspective, versus what I knew.

485
00:25:58,014 --> 00:25:59,015
Yeah.

486
00:26:00,559 --> 00:26:02,310
What was going on in the '70s

487
00:26:02,394 --> 00:26:06,690
was that, as black families like ours
were moving into neighborhoods,

488
00:26:06,773 --> 00:26:09,276
white families were being scared away.

489
00:26:09,359 --> 00:26:11,820
They were being told,
"Sell your home quick.

490
00:26:11,903 --> 00:26:14,322
Your property values
are going to go down."

491
00:26:14,406 --> 00:26:17,826
And so they fled further to the suburbs.

492
00:26:18,118 --> 00:26:22,539
You can even see it in class pictures
of my kindergarten class

493
00:26:22,622 --> 00:26:24,541
and my eighth-grade class.

494
00:26:24,874 --> 00:26:28,211
I mean, it does something to kids like me,

495
00:26:28,628 --> 00:26:30,338
and we have to remember that

496
00:26:30,422 --> 00:26:34,217
as we are pointing out people
who belong and don't belong.

497
00:26:34,301 --> 00:26:36,136
Because my family, sadly,

498
00:26:36,219 --> 00:26:40,056
was one of those families,
to some, who didn't belong.

499
00:26:42,851 --> 00:26:45,353
I ended up going to Princeton.

500
00:26:47,814 --> 00:26:51,151
I was one of a handful
of minority students.

501
00:26:51,568 --> 00:26:55,697
It was the first time in my life
where I stood out like that.

502
00:26:59,576 --> 00:27:02,162
I learned that
